Ùª­jAttributesÙ¯‚€öpExtended SummaryÙ¯‚€ögMethodsÙ¯‚€öeNotesÙ¯‚ˆÙ¹‚Ù§x}Both the Hilbert  or homomorphic   methods require selection of an FFT length to estimate the complex cepstrum of the filter.€Ù¹‚‡Ù§xIIn the case of the Hilbert method, the deviation from the ideal spectrum Ù¡gepsilonÙ§x, is related to the number of stopband zeros Ù¡fn_stopÙ§p and FFT length Ù¡en_fftÙ§k as::      €ÙÀxepsilon = 2. * n_stop / n_fftÙ¹‚…Ù§x?For example, with 100 stopband zeros and a FFT length of 2048, Ù¡pepsilon = 0.0976Ù§x¨. If we conservatively assume that the number of stopband zeros is one less than the filter length, we can take the FFT length to be the next power of 2 that satisfies Ù¡lepsilon=0.01Ù§k as::      €ÙÀx;n_fft = 2 ** int(np.ceil(np.log2(2 * (len(h) - 1) / 0.01)))Ù¹‚ƒÙ§xjThis gives reasonable results for both the Hilbert and homomorphic methods, and gives the value used when Ù¡jn_fft=NoneÙ§a.€Ù¹‚Ù§x˜Alternative implementations exist for creating minimum-phase filters, including zero inversion  and spectral factorization  . For more information, see:€Ù·xEhttp://dspguru.com/dsp/howtos/how-to-design-minimum-phase-fir-filtersöpOther ParametersÙ¯‚€öjParametersÙ¯‚ƒÙ°ƒahearrayÙ¹‚Ù§x%Linear-phase FIR filter coefficients.€Ù°ƒfmethodx{'hilbert', 'homomorphic'}‚Ù¹‚Ù§rThe method to use:€Ù·Šw'homomorphic' (default)x9    This method [4]_ [5]_ works best with filters with anx>    odd number of taps, and the resulting minimum phase filterx?    will have a magnitude response that approximates the squarex9    root of the the original filter's magnitude response.`i'hilbert'x;    This method [1]_ is designed to be used with equiripplex8    filters (e.g., from `remez`) with unity or zero gainl    regions.Ù°ƒen_fftcintÙ¹‚Ù§xrThe number of points to use for the FFT. Should be at least a few times larger than the signal length (see Notes).€öfRaisesÙ¯‚€öhReceivesÙ¯‚€ögReturnsÙ¯‚Ù°ƒih_minimumearrayÙ¹‚ƒÙ§x5The minimum-phase version of the filt